1. Check for MIG Compatibility
First, verify if your assigned GPU supports MIG (required: Ampere architecture or newer). 
NVIDIA Docs
NVIDIA Docs
 +2
python
# Check GPU type and if MIG is supported
!nvidia-smi -q | grep -i "MIG Mode"
Use code with caution.

2. Basic Project: Enabling & Partitioning MIG
If you are on an A100/H100 instance, you can use these commands to partition your GPU into smaller, isolated instances. 
Scaleway
Scaleway
python
# 1. Enable MIG mode (requires root, usually works in Colab terminal or as ! command)
!nvidia-smi -i 0 -mig 1

# 2. List possible profiles (e.g., 1g.5gb, 2g.10gb, 3g.20gb)
!nvidia-smi mig -lgip

# 3. Create a partition (Example: 2 instances of 1g.5gb)
# Profile ID 19 is typically the 1g.5gb slice on an A100
!nvidia-smi mig -cgi 19,19 -C

# 4. Verify your new virtual GPU instances
!nvidia-smi -L
Use code with caution.

Note: In a standard Colab environment, you may lack the permissions to change the global MIG state. This is best executed on a Deep Learning VM or Google Compute Engine instance where you have full sudo access. 
